= Abstract
WebGPU is a recent cross-platform GPU standard that promises native-level compute performance in both desktop and browser environments, but it has seen little use for scientific workloads. We test that promise by implementing a complete Barnes–Hut gravitational N-body solver and measuring where the abstraction costs actually fall. Our implementation builds a Linear Bounding Volume Hierarchy on the GPU every timestep using Karras's parallel method, evaluates forces via BVH traversal, and integrates with a symplectic leapfrog, all from a single C++/WGSL codebase that compiles to both native desktop and browser targets. On an Apple M2 Macbook Air, we benchmark four WebGPU implementations (wgpu-native, Dawn, Chrome, Safari) and compare against a native Metal Barnes–Hut solver. The WebGPU abstraction costs 2.0$times$ at $N = 1000$ but outperforms the Metal baseline above $N = 5000$, reaching 2.9$times$ faster at $N = 100000$ thanks to a fully GPU-resident tree pipeline. Force evaluation dominates step time (94–99%); LBVH construction stays below 0.35 ms regardless of particle count. In the browser, Chrome is competitive at small $N$ but scales worse, settling at a 1.4$times$ overhead by $N = 100000$. Numerical fidelity is limited by both 32-bit precision and the tree force approximation. These results show that WebGPU can support interactive galactic dynamics simulation — including parallel tree construction and hierarchical force evaluation — without specialised hardware or vendor lock-in.
